  ],
  "body_sections": [
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Raises an AssertionError if two array_like objects are not equal."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Summary"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Given two array_like objects, check that the shape is equal and all\nelements of these objects are equal (but see the Notes for the special\nhandling of a scalar). An exception is raised at shape mismatch or\nconflicting values. In contrast to the standard usage in numpy, NaNs\nare compared like numbers, no assertion is raised if both objects have\nNaNs in the same positions."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The usual caution for verifying equality with floating point numbers is\nadvised."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "argument_inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "When either "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "actual"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " or "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "desired"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is already an instance of"
            }
          ],
          "content_blocks": [
            {
              "inline": [
                {
                  "external_url": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.ndarray.html",
                  "href": "",
                  "kind": "link",
                  "target": "ndarray",
                  "text": "we.ndarray"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " and "
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "desired"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " is not a "
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "dict"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": ", the behavior of\n"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "assert_equal(actual, desired)"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " is identical to the behavior of this\nfunction. Otherwise, this function performs "
                },
                {
                  "external_url": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.asanyarray.html",
                  "href": "",
                  "kind": "link",
                  "target": "asanyarray",
                  "text": "we.asanyarray"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " on the\ninputs before comparison, whereas "
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "assert_equal"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " defines special\ncomparison rules for common Python types. For example, only\n"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "assert_equal"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " can be used to compare nested Python lists. In new code,\nconsider using only "
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "assert_equal"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": ", explicitly converting either\n"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "actual"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " or "
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "desired"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": " to arrays if the behavior of "
                },
                {
                  "kind": "code",
                  "text": "assert_array_equal"
                },
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "text": "\nis desired."
                }
              ],
              "type": "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "directive": "note",
          "options": [],
          "raw_source": ".. note:: When either `actual` or `desired` is already an instance of\n    `we.ndarray` and `desired` is not a ``dict``, the behavior of\n    ``assert_equal(actual, desired)`` is identical to the behavior of this\n    function. Otherwise, this function performs `we.asanyarray` on the\n    inputs before comparison, whereas `assert_equal` defines special\n    comparison rules for common Python types. For example, only\n    `assert_equal` can be used to compare nested Python lists. In new code,\n    consider using only `assert_equal`, explicitly converting either\n    `actual` or `desired` to arrays if the behavior of `assert_array_equal`\n    is desired.",
          "supported": true,
          "type": "directive_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Extended Summary"
    },
